Business Day

Ouster at AOL, but Where Does Trail End?

By DAVID D. KIRKPATRICKSEPT. 1, 2002



Continue reading the main story
Share This Page

Continue reading the main story









BEFORE he came to America Online in 1995, David M. Colburn was a corporate lawyer in Palo Alto, Calif., known for his meticulousness, his aggression and his eccentricity. Commuting from Los Angeles, he shaved once a week, drove a beat-up clunker and slept in a cheap motel. In an office of suits and khakis, he customarily wore cowboy boots with pinstripe suit pants, polo shirts and an earring. He became notorious for screaming and swearing at younger lawyers for offenses like the failure to underline the phrase ''provided, however'' while preparing a contract, lawyers who worked with him said.The same no-holds-barred approach to business helped propel Mr. Colburn's rise at AOL, where he became the chief deal maker, in charge of its business affairs department. It may also have led to his disgrace. Three weeks ago, he was ousted after federal investigators and an internal inquiry by lawyers for AOL Time Warner began looking into the possibility that deals he negotiated may have inappropriately inflated the company's revenue.Now his departure has raised the question of whether investigators will stop at Mr. Colburn or turn their attention to the executives around and above him. It is as yet unclear whether Mr. Colburn concealed financial details from others at America Online. But people who worked with him said he was always more of a builder than an architect, better at details and execution than devising strategy on his own. And at AOL, he collaborated closely with other executives, including those in charge of the company's finances and programming, they said. All signed off on the structure of all his major deals.Mr. Colburn was recruited to AOL by Miles R. Gilburne, a mentor for most of Mr. Colburn's career in the legal world. Mr. Gilburne became AOL's chief corporate strategist, and Mr. Colburn helped him hammer out the details of some of AOL's biggest deals. Robert W. Pittman, the former president of AOL who became chief operating officer of AOL Time Warner, promoted Mr. Colburn to head AOL's business affairs department and supervised his work. J. Michael Kelly signed off on the accounting for all Mr. Colburn's major transactions as the chief financial officer of AOL before it acquired Time Warner and of the combined company afterward.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

Each of these executives declined to comment last week on their roles.Some of Mr. Colburn's colleagues at AOL -- and even some who have negotiated against him -- said they felt he had been unfairly singled out, in part because of his sometimes abrasive style. Continue reading the main story







Advertisement

Continue reading the main story





''People turned on him,'' said Dan Borislow, former chief executive of Tel-Save who had sat opposite Mr. Colburn in several negotiations. ''Every single transaction that he did was approved by somebody in finance. David is an excellent, competent person who covers himself very well. And he is a jerk. That is why he is in trouble. If the guy was a nice guy, he wouldn't be in the news.''Mr. Colburn's friends, including some current AOL executives, say he was neither trained as an accountant nor responsible for the company's financial reports, putting him a step removed from potential accounting misdeeds.''David Colburn would not pass an introductory accounting exam,'' said Allan B. Koltin, an old friend who is now a consultant to accounting and law firms. ''He wasn't high enough in the executive ranks to approve the accounting for transactions of any magnitude. What really smells about what AOL is doing is they are trying to say, 'We had one or two bad seeds among us and we have washed our hands of them and now we are clean and pure again.' ''On Aug. 8, AOL Time Warner's top executives asked Mr. Colburn to stop coming to work, and fired him the next day. Company executives said he was asked to leave partly because a tip from an employee had turned up three questionable transactions -- one with WorldCom and two with still-undisclosed companies -- bearing Mr. Colburn's fingerprints. The company said the deals might have overstated its revenue by $49 million over the 18 months ending last March. Lawyers for AOL Time Warner have sealed Mr. Colburn's office to search it for evidence, company executives said.The questionable $49 million that AOL Time Warner has identified is less than 1 percent of the AOL division's annual revenue and, in contrast to companies like Enron or WorldCom, at AOL there is no clear evidence of wrongdoing. But AOL Time Warner is conducting an internal investigation into accounting at its AOL division over the last two years, alongside those by the Securities and Exchange Commission and the Justice Department.Investors are anxious about the investigations in part because AOL has pushed the limits of accounting rules before. In 2000, the company settled an unrelated S.E.C. inquiry by paying a fine and pledging not to violate any securities laws in the future. Securities law experts say such settlements often lead both the S.E.C. and the Justice Department to take a tougher stance the next time a problem occurs.ONE question at issue, people involved with both the S.E.C. and internal inquiries have said, is whether AOL might have overstated its results by trading goods or services with other companies at inflated prices and recording the prices as revenue. The practice is known as round-tripping because money paid out as an expense effectively comes back, recorded as sales and artificially bolstering the top line. It is an especially thorny issue for AOL because the company prided itself on doing reciprocal business -- for example, selling advertising to many of its telecommunications and technology suppliers.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

Mr. Colburn, the point man in charge of negotiating advertising sales agreements for AOL, played a crucial role in most of AOL's reciprocal deals, including its transactions with WorldCom. But people who worked with him in the past say his maverick persona did not necessarily extend to his approach to his work.''Here was a really conservative lawyer who knew the law and counseled clients not to take legal risks,'' said Lior Nuchi, a lawyer who worked with Mr. Colburn in the Palo Alto office of Weil, Gotshal & Manges before 1995. ''The other thing I learned about David is he always made himself a strong No. 2. I never saw him as a guy who wanted to be the primary decision maker.''MR. COLBURN spent most of his career as a No. 2 to Mr. Gilburne, who was a close adviser to AOL's chairman, Stephen M. Case. After graduating from the University of Wisconsin Law School, Mr. Colburn began working for Mr. Gilburn at a Los Angeles law firm. When Mr. Gilburne left to start a venture capital firm, Mr. Colburn did his legal work. Then Mr. Colburn followed Mr. Gilburne when he opened a Palo Alto office for Weil, Gotshal and again when he joined AOL.By then, Mr. Colburn had practiced law for about 15 years as an associate, nearly twice as long as it often takes to become a partner. When Mr. Gilburne left for AOL, Mr. Colburn finally had a strong chance to make partner, but he gave it up to follow his mentor, Mr. Nuchi said.At AOL, Mr. Colburn and Mr. Gilburne made an oddly complementary pair, several people who worked with them said. Mr. Gilburne is a broad, strategic thinker with a quiet, professorial demeanor. He is prone to stroking his beard, alluding to Shakespeare and making Delphic comments about the technological future. Mr. Colburn, on the other hand, is as volatile as Mr. Gilburne is sedate. People who worked with them said Mr. Colburn paced conference rooms with bleary eyes and a five o'clock shadow. He was known for wearing Armani suits over black T-shirts depicting cartoon characters. And Mr. Colburn was also as intensely focused on details as his mentor was on the big picture.Mr. Gilburne sometimes joked that his favorite deals were the hardest ones to understand, people who worked with him said, and he worked closely with Mr. Colburn to iron out the structure of AOL's biggest and most esoteric transactions. In November 1998, for example, the two executives shuttled back and forth between the Silicon Valley headquarters of Netscape Communications and Sun Microsystems playing their contemplative good-cop, aggressive bad-cop roles as they worked out a complicated three-way deal for the sale of one company and a partnership with the other. The deal also involved some of the issues now drawing attention from securities regulators.
