In one part of the deal, Sun agreed to pay AOL more than $310 million a year as part of a three-year partnership called iPlanet. AOL treated the payments as recurring revenue until last January, when AOL Time Warner announced that the partnership would not continue. In a simultaneous deal, AOL agreed to buy $500 million in computer equipment from Sun at list price, even though companies like AOL usually buy at a discount of more than 30 percent. In turn, Sun agreed to pay AOL $350 million in licensing, marketing and advertising fees, raising the possibility that AOL was effectively getting back some of its expenditures to bolster its own revenue.An AOL Time Warner spokesman declined to comment on specific deals but said the company accounted for the Sun transaction appropriately. A spokeswoman for Sun said it accounted for the deals appropriately.Although Mr. Gilburne recruited Mr. Colburn to AOL, Mr. Pittman beefed up the company's business affairs division and tapped Mr. Colburn to run it. When Mr. Pittman joined America Online in 1996 as president of its America Online Networks division, he quickly set about streamlining its freewheeling management. He introduced a new focus on bottom-line results and increased each executive's accountability, several AOL executives said. He also instilled a rigorous reporting structure, imposing order on fractious fiefs within AOL, and he prided himself on his ability to exhort his employees to greater accomplishments. Those who disappointed him were replaced.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

But Mr. Pittman lavishly rewarded executives who did meet their quarterly goals. Mr. Colburn earned enough from AOL stock options to hire 'N Sync and the Dave Matthews Band to perform for the birthday parties of two of his children.At the time, AOL was shifting its business model to selling advertising as well as subscriptions, and Mr. Pittman expanded the business affairs division partly to coordinate the efforts of the company's advertising sales force and the executives who controlled the content on various parts of its service. Analysts and company executives credit Mr. Pittman and Mr. Colburn with orchestrating much of AOL's remarkable success at increasing its advertising revenue during the boom years from 1996 through 1999, partly through Mr. Colburn's bare-knuckled negotiating.Mr. Pittman also championed the idea that it was simply good business for AOL to take equity in its advertisers and sell ads to its suppliers, two-way transactions that became a specialty of Mr. Colburn's business affairs division.In 1996, Mr. Pittman introduced Mr. Colburn to Mr. Borislow, the former chief executive of Tel-Save, which is now called Talk.com. Mr. Pittman had agreed in principle to sell advertising to Tel-Save in exchange for a combination of cash and warrants to buy its stock, AOL's first deal of the kind, then turned the negotiations over to Mr. Colburn to work out. Mr. Colburn managed to wring an upfront payment of $100 million from Mr. Borislow, making him a hero within AOL, and Mr. Pittman trumpeted the victory.The S.E.C. later challenged how AOL accounted for its equity in Tel-Save, forcing AOL to restate its earnings for the last quarter of 1997 downward by $7 million. Harvey L. Pitt, then in private practice and now S.E.C. chairman, represented AOL in settling the matter.After AOL acquired Time Warner, Mr. Pittman again promoted Mr. Colburn, to head of business affairs for the combined company. Executives at the parent company have said that Mr. Pittman personally worked hard supporting Mr. Colburn to push through its major companywide advertising deals, including an agreement to sell advertising from both the AOL division and the Time Warner businesses to WorldCom. In another reciprocal transaction, AOL simultaneously agreed to continue buying telecommunications services from WorldCom, and AOL Time Warner executives have said that a two-way transaction with WorldCom contributed to the questionable $49 million the company discovered.AOL Time Warner executives and Mr. Pittman's friends said, however, that he was seldom personally involved in the details of accounting. One AOL Time Warner executive said the questionable transaction with WorldCom amounted to less than half the $49 million, possibly representing some side deal. Such relatively insignificant sums would be well below Mr. Pittman's review, executives said.MR. KELLY, the chief financial officer of AOL and then AOL Time Warner, was the executive most directly responsible for the accuracy of the company's accounting. He joined AOL in June 1998. The son of an F.B.I. agent, he, like Mr. Colburn, could sometimes be hot-tempered, AOL Time Warner executives said.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

AOL Time Warner executives said that it was Mr. Colburn's job to try to do everything possible to post strong results, and it was Mr. Kelly's job to stop him at the limits of accounting rules. Mr. Kelly signed off on all of its major deals and its financial reports until December 2001, when he was demoted to chief operating officer of the AOL division after a burst of anger at a Wall Street analyst.But AOL Time Warner executives noted that Mr. Kelly was no longer chief financial officer for five of the six quarters during which the company has discovered questionable revenue. Executives said Mr. Kelley had instituted a new, stricter program of financial controls at AOL. They added that the internal policing Mr. Kelly initiated helped block a number of creative transactions involving advertising sales. AOL Time Warner executives and friends of Mr. Kelly said he often clashed with Mr. Colburn over business matters. Mr. Pittman was then called in to resolve their disputes.Mr. Kelly's friends add that a chief financial officer is only as good as the information he is given.Last week, with no clear evidence of significant wrongdoing at AOL, lawyers said it was still too soon to assess the wisdom of AOL Time Warner's decision to remove Mr. Colburn. Martin R. Pollner, a defense lawyer who handles white-collar crime cases, said the firing of Mr. Colburn demonstrates that AOL Time Warner is cleaning house. But it may also encourage Mr. Colburn to cooperate with federal investigators looking at AOL.''It sends a signal to the government that this is someone to talk to, and the game of 'let's make a deal' begins,'' Mr. Pollner said. Continue reading the main story






